{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a41fdaba-21fa-441f-b667-06e5caae62be","content":"The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** crash dumps, not analyzing them. It won't help here.\n\nFor **analyzing** a `.dmp` file, here are your best options:\n\n1. **`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n   dotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n   ```\n   Then use commands like `clrstack`, `pe` (print exception), `dumpheap`, etc.\n\n2. **`lldb` with SOS** (Linux/macOS):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet-sos install\n   lldb --core your-file.dmp\n   ```\n\n3. **WinDbg / Visual Studio** (Windows) — open the `.dmp` directly.\n\n**Quick triage commands** inside `dotnet-dump analyze`:\n- `pe` — print the last exception\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack\n- `threads` — list all threads\n- `dso` — dump stack objects\n\nWould you like me to walk you through running any of these tools on your dump file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36b66326-7d3e-4f43-a3b2-44f7689eccb6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description explicitly says:\n\n- **USE FOR**: enabling automatic crash dumps, capturing dumps, setting up dump collection\n- **DO NOT USE FOR**: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze, profiling or tracing\n\nSo the `dump-collect` skill is not appropriate here since it's for collecting dumps, not analyzing them.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":414},"id":"cd26c00a-97cf-4479-829a-1152786859f1","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:01:11.993Z","parentId":"751f98c6-0173-4e11-9749-b1a71a4c9268"}
